[src:greens-functions/dirichlet-problem] In mathematics, a **Dirichlet problem** asks for a function which solves a specified partial differential equation (PDE) in the interior of a given region that takes prescribed values on the boundary of the region.
[src:greens-functions/dirichlet-problem] The Dirichlet problem can be solved for many PDEs, although originally it was posed for Laplace's equation.
[src:greens-functions/dirichlet-problem] This requirement is called the Dirichlet boundary condition.
[src:greens-functions/dirichlet-problem] The main issue is to prove the existence of a solution; uniqueness can be proven using the maximum principle.
[src:greens-functions/dirichlet-problem] The Dirichlet problem goes back to George Green, who studied the problem on general domains with general boundary conditions in his *Essay on the Application of Mathematical Analysis to the Theories of Electricity and Magnetism*, published in 1828.
[src:greens-functions/dirichlet-problem] He reduced the problem into a problem of constructing what we now call Green's functions, and argued that Green's function exists for any domain.
[src:greens-functions/dirichlet-problem] His methods were not rigorous by today's standards, but the ideas were highly influential in the subsequent developments.
[src:greens-functions/dirichlet-problem] Lord Kelvin and Dirichlet suggested a solution to the problem by a variational method based on the minimization of "Dirichlet's energy".
[src:greens-functions/dirichlet-problem] According to Hans Freudenthal (in the *Dictionary of Scientific Biography*, vol.
[src:greens-functions/dirichlet-problem] 11), Bernhard Riemann was the first mathematician who solved this variational problem based on a method which he called Dirichlet's principle.
[src:greens-functions/dirichlet-problem] The existence of a unique solution is very plausible by the "physical argument": any charge distribution on the boundary should, by the laws of electrostatics, determine an electrical potential as solution.
[src:greens-functions/dirichlet-problem] However, Karl Weierstrass found a flaw in Riemann's argument, and a rigorous proof of existence was found only in 1900 by David Hilbert, using his direct method in the calculus of variations.
[src:greens-functions/dirichlet-problem] It turns out that the existence of a solution depends delicately on the smoothness of the boundary and the prescribed data.
[src:greens-functions/dirichlet-problem] is the derivative of the Green's function along the inward-pointing unit normal vector ${\widehat {n}}$ .
[src:greens-functions/dirichlet-problem] The integration is performed on the boundary, with measure $ds$ .
[src:greens-functions/dirichlet-problem] Such a Green's function is usually a sum of the free-field Green's function and a harmonic solution to the differential equation.
[src:greens-functions/dirichlet-problem] The Dirichlet problem for harmonic functions always has a solution, and that solution is unique, when the boundary is sufficiently smooth and $f(s)$ is continuous.
