[src:greens-functions/green-s-function] Green's functions are named after the British mathematician George Green, who first developed the concept in the 1820s.
[src:greens-functions/green-s-function] In the modern study of linear partial differential equations, Green's functions are studied largely from the point of view of fundamental solutions instead, which take into account the modern language of the theory of distributions or generalized functions.
[src:greens-functions/green-s-function] In quantum field theory, Green's functions take the role of propagators, also referred to as two-point (correlation) functions.
[src:greens-functions/green-s-function] If the kernel of *L* is non-trivial, then the Green's function is not unique.
[src:greens-functions/green-s-function] However, in practice, some combination of symmetry, boundary conditions and/or other externally imposed criteria will give a unique Green's function.
[src:greens-functions/green-s-function] Green's functions may be categorized by a Green's function number according to the type of boundary conditions being satisfied.
[src:greens-functions/green-s-function] Green's functions are not necessarily functions of a real variable but are generally understood in the sense of distributions.
[src:greens-functions/green-s-function] Green's functions are also useful tools in solving wave equations and diffusion equations.
[src:greens-functions/green-s-function] In quantum mechanics, Green's function of the Hamiltonian is a key concept with important links to the concept of density of states.
[src:greens-functions/green-s-function] The Green's function as used in physics is usually defined with the opposite sign, instead.
