[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] The **method of images** (or **method of mirror images**) is a mathematical tool for solving differential equations, in which boundary conditions are satisfied by combining a solution not restricted by the boundary conditions with its possibly weighted mirror image.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] Generally, original singularities are inside the domain of interest but the function is made to satisfy boundary conditions by placing additional singularities outside the domain of interest.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] Typically the locations of these additional singularities are determined as the virtual location of the original singularities as viewed in a mirror placed at the location of the boundary conditions.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] Most typically, the mirror is a hyperplane or hypersphere.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] The **method of images** can also be used in solving discrete problems with boundary conditions, such counting the number of restricted discrete random walks.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] The method of image charges is used in electrostatics to simply calculate or visualize the distribution of the electric field of a charge in the vicinity of a conducting surface.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] It is based on the fact that the tangential component of the electrical field on the surface of a conductor is zero, and that an electric field E in some region is uniquely defined by its normal component over the surface that confines this region (the uniqueness theorem).
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] The method of images may also be used in magnetostatics for calculating the magnetic field of a magnet that is close to a superconducting surface.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] The superconductor in so-called Meissner state is an ideal diamagnet into which the magnetic field does not penetrate.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] Therefore, the normal component of the magnetic field on its surface should be zero.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] Then the image of the magnet should be mirrored.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] The force between the magnet and the superconducting surface is therefore repulsive.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] Comparing to the case of the charge dipole above a flat conducting surface, the mirrored magnetization vector can be thought as due to an additional sign change of an axial vector.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] In order to take into account the magnetic flux pinning phenomenon in type-II superconductors, the frozen mirror image method can be used.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] Environmental engineers are often interested in the reflection (and sometimes the absorption) of a contaminant plume off of an impenetrable (no-flux) boundary.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] A quick way to model this reflection is with the method of images.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] The reflections, or *images*, are oriented in space such that they perfectly replace any mass (from the real plume) passing through a given boundary.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] A single boundary will necessitate a single image.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] Two or more boundaries produce infinite images.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] However, for the purposes of modeling mass transport—such as the spread of a contaminant spill in a lake—it may be unnecessary to include an infinite set of images when there are multiple relevant boundaries.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] For example, to represent the reflection within a certain threshold of physical accuracy, one might choose to include only the primary and secondary images.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] The simplest case is a single boundary in 1-dimensional space.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] In this case, only one image is possible.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] If as time elapses, a mass approaches the boundary, then an image can appropriately describe the reflection of that mass back across the boundary.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] Another simple example is a single boundary in 2-dimensional space.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] Again, since there is only a single boundary, only one image is necessary.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] This describes a smokestack, whose effluent "reflects" in the atmosphere off of the impenetrable ground, and is otherwise approximately unbounded.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] Finally, we consider a mass release in 1-dimensional space bounded to its left and right by impenetrable boundaries.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] There are two primary images, each replacing the mass of the original release reflecting through each boundary.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] There are two secondary images, each replacing the mass of one of the primary images flowing through the opposite boundary.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] There are also two tertiary images (replacing the mass lost by the secondary images), two quaternary images (replacing the mass lost by the tertiary images), and so on ad infinitum.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] For a given system, once all of the images are carefully oriented, the concentration field is given by summing the mass releases (the *true* plume in addition to all of the images) within the specified boundaries.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] This concentration field is only physically accurate within the boundaries; the field outside the boundaries is non-physical and irrelevant for most engineering purposes.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] This method is a specific application of Green's functions.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] The method of images works well when the boundary is a flat surface and the distribution has a geometric center.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] This allows for simple mirror-like reflection of the distribution to satisfy a variety of boundary conditions.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] Consider the simple 1D case illustrated in the graphic where there is a distribution of $\langle c\rangle$ as a function of x and a single boundary located at $x_{b}$ with the real domain such that $x\geq x_{b}$ and the image domain $x<x_{b}$ .
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] Consider the solution $f(\pm x+x_{0},t)$ to satisfy the linear differential equation for any $x_{0}$ , but not necessarily the boundary condition.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] Note these distributions are typical in models that assume a Gaussian distribution.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] This is particularly common in environmental engineering, especially in atmospheric flows that use Gaussian plume models.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] This states that the derivative of our scalar function y will have no derivative in the normal direction to a wall.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] Thus, the perfectly reflecting boundary condition is satisfied.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] Thus this boundary condition is also satisfied.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] The method of images can be used in discrete cases.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] For example, the number of random walks that start at position 0, take steps of size ±1, continue for a total of n steps, and end at position k is given by the binomial coefficient ${\binom {n}{(n+k)/2}}$ assuming that |*k*| ≤ *n* and *n* + *k* is even.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] Suppose we have the boundary condition that walks are prohibited from stepping to −1 during any part of the walk.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] The number of restricted walks can be calculated by starting with the number of unrestricted walks that start at position 0 and end at position k and subtracting the number of unrestricted walks that start at position −2 and end at position k.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] This is because, for any given number of steps, exactly as many unrestricted positively weighted walks as unrestricted negatively weighted walks will reach −1; they are mirror images of each other.
[src:greens-functions/method-of-images] As such, these negatively weighted walks cancel out precisely those positively weighted walks that our boundary condition has prohibited.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] In quantum mechanics and quantum field theory, the **propagator** is a function that specifies the probability amplitude for a particle to travel from one place to another in a given period of time, or to travel with a certain energy and momentum.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] In Feynman diagrams, which serve to calculate the rate of collisions in quantum field theory, virtual particles contribute their propagator to the rate of the scattering event described by the respective diagram.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] Propagators may also be viewed as the inverse of the wave operator appropriate to the particle, and are, therefore, often called *(causal) Green's functions* (called "*causal*" to distinguish it from the elliptic Laplacian Green's function).
[src:greens-functions/propagator] In non-relativistic quantum mechanics, the propagator gives the probability amplitude for a particle to travel from one spatial point (x') at one time (t') to another spatial point (x) at a later time (t).
[src:greens-functions/propagator] The kernel of the above Schrödinger differential operator in the big parentheses is denoted by *K*(*x*, *t* ;*x′*, *t′*) and called the **propagator**.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] This propagator may also be written as the transition amplitude $K(x,t;x',t')={\big \langle }x{\big |}U(t,t'){\big |}x'{\big \rangle },$ where *U*(*t*, *t′*) is the unitary time-evolution operator for the system taking states at time t′ to states at time t.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] where L denotes the Lagrangian and the boundary conditions are given by *q*(*t*) = *x*, *q*(*t′*) = *x′*.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] The paths that are summed over move only forwards in time and are integrated with the differential $D[q(t)]$ following the path in time.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] The propagator lets one find the wave function of a system, given an initial wave function and a time interval.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] If *K*(*x*, *t*; *x*′, *t*′) only depends on the difference *x* − *x′*, this is a convolution of the initial wave function and the propagator.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] In relativistic quantum mechanics and quantum field theory the propagators are Lorentz-invariant.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] They give the amplitude for a particle to travel between two spacetime events.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] In quantum field theory, the theory of a free (or non-interacting) scalar field is a useful and simple example which serves to illustrate the concepts needed for more complicated theories.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] There are a number of possible propagators for free scalar field theory.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] The position space propagators are Green's functions for the Klein–Gordon equation.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] We shall restrict attention to 4-dimensional Minkowski spacetime.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] This equation can be inverted in the sense of distributions, noting that the equation *xf*(*x*) = 1 has the solution (see Sokhotski–Plemelj theorem) $f(x)={\frac {1}{x\pm i\varepsilon }}={\frac {1}{x}}\mp i\pi \delta (x),$ with ε implying the limit to zero.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] Below, we discuss the right choice of the sign arising from causality requirements.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] The different choices for how to deform the integration contour in the above expression lead to various forms for the propagator.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] The choice of contour is usually phrased in terms of the $p_{0}$ integral.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] The integrand then has two poles at $p_{0}=\pm {\sqrt {{\vec {p}}^{2}+m^{2}}},$ so different choices of how to avoid these lead to different propagators.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] A contour going clockwise over both poles gives the **causal retarded propagator**.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] This is zero if x-y is spacelike or y is to the future of x, so it is zero if *x* ⁰< *y* ⁰.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] A contour going anti-clockwise under both poles gives the **causal advanced propagator**.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] This is zero if x-y is spacelike or if y is to the past of x, so it is zero if *x* ⁰> *y* ⁰.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] This expression can also be expressed in terms of the vacuum expectation value of the commutator of the free scalar field.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] A contour going under the left pole and over the right pole gives the **Feynman propagator**, introduced by Richard Feynman in 1948.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] Here, *H*1(1) is a Hankel function and *K*1 is a modified Bessel function.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] This expression is Lorentz invariant, as long as the field operators commute with one another when the points x and y are separated by a spacelike interval.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] The propagator may also be derived using the path integral formulation of quantum theory.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] The Fourier transform of the position space propagators can be thought of as propagators in momentum space.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] These take a much simpler form than the position space propagators.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] They are often written with an explicit ε term although this is understood to be a reminder about which integration contour is appropriate (see above).
[src:greens-functions/propagator] This ε term is included to incorporate boundary conditions and causality (see below).
[src:greens-functions/propagator] For purposes of Feynman diagram calculations, it is usually convenient to write these with an additional overall factor of i (conventions vary).
[src:greens-functions/propagator] The Feynman propagator has some properties that seem baffling at first.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] In particular, unlike the commutator, the propagator is *nonzero* outside of the light cone, though it falls off rapidly for spacelike intervals.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] Interpreted as an amplitude for particle motion, this translates to the virtual particle travelling faster than light.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] It is not immediately obvious how this can be reconciled with causality: can we use faster-than-light virtual particles to send faster-than-light messages?
[src:greens-functions/propagator] The answer is no: while in classical mechanics the intervals along which particles and causal effects can travel are the same, this is no longer true in quantum field theory, where it is commutators that determine which operators can affect one another.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] So what *does* the spacelike part of the propagator represent?
[src:greens-functions/propagator] In QFT the vacuum is an active participant, and particle numbers and field values are related by an uncertainty principle; field values are uncertain even for particle number *zero*.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] There is a nonzero probability amplitude to find a significant fluctuation in the vacuum value of the field Φ(*x*) if one measures it locally (or, to be more precise, if one measures an operator obtained by averaging the field over a small region).
[src:greens-functions/propagator] Furthermore, the dynamics of the fields tend to favor spatially correlated fluctuations to some extent.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] The nonzero time-ordered product for spacelike-separated fields then just measures the amplitude for a nonlocal correlation in these vacuum fluctuations, analogous to an EPR correlation.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] Indeed, the propagator is often called a *two-point correlation function* for the free field.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] Since, by the postulates of quantum field theory, all observable operators commute with each other at spacelike separation, messages can no more be sent through these correlations than they can through any other EPR correlations; the correlations are in random variables.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] Regarding virtual particles, the propagator at spacelike separation can be thought of as a means of calculating the amplitude for creating a virtual particle-antiparticle pair that eventually disappears into the vacuum, or for detecting a virtual pair emerging from the vacuum.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] In Feynman's language, such creation and annihilation processes are equivalent to a virtual particle wandering backward and forward through time, which can take it outside of the light cone.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] However, no signaling back in time is allowed.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] This is the usual definition but normalised by a factor of $\varepsilon$ .
[src:greens-functions/propagator] Then the rule is that one only takes the limit $\varepsilon \to 0$ at the end of a calculation.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] The most common use of the propagator is in calculating probability amplitudes for particle interactions using Feynman diagrams.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] These calculations are usually carried out in momentum space.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] In general, the amplitude gets a factor of the propagator for every *internal line*, that is, every line that does not represent an incoming or outgoing particle in the initial or final state.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] It will also get a factor proportional to, and similar in form to, an interaction term in the theory's Lagrangian for every internal vertex where lines meet.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] These prescriptions are known as *Feynman rules*.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] Internal lines correspond to virtual particles.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] Since the propagator does not vanish for combinations of energy and momentum disallowed by the classical equations of motion, we say that the virtual particles are allowed to be off shell.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] In fact, since the propagator is obtained by inverting the wave equation, in general, it will have singularities on shell.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] The energy carried by the particle in the propagator can even be *negative*.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] This can be interpreted simply as the case in which, instead of a particle going one way, its antiparticle is going the *other* way, and therefore carrying an opposing flow of positive energy.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] The propagator encompasses both possibilities.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] It does mean that one has to be careful about minus signs for the case of fermions, whose propagators are not even functions in the energy and momentum (see below).
[src:greens-functions/propagator] Virtual particles conserve energy and momentum.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] Therefore, every loop in a Feynman diagram requires an integral over a continuum of possible energies and momenta.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] In general, these integrals of products of propagators can diverge, a situation that must be handled by the process of renormalization.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] If the particle possesses spin then its propagator is in general somewhat more complicated, as it will involve the particle's spin or polarization indices.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] where *I*4 is the unit matrix in four dimensions, and employing the Feynman slash notation.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] This is the Dirac equation for a delta function source in spacetime.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] where on the right-hand side an integral representation of the four-dimensional delta function is used.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] The *iε* downstairs is a prescription for how to handle the poles in the complex *p*0-plane.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] It automatically yields the Feynman contour of integration by shifting the poles appropriately.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] It should be remembered that this expression is just shorthand notation for (*γ**μ**p**μ* − *m*)−1.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] "One over matrix" is otherwise nonsensical.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] The propagator for a gauge boson in a gauge theory depends on the choice of convention to fix the gauge.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] The propagator for a massive vector field can be derived from the Stueckelberg Lagrangian.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] With these general forms one obtains the propagators in unitary gauge for *λ* = 0, the propagator in Feynman or 't Hooft gauge for *λ* = 1 and in Landau or Lorenz gauge for *λ* = ∞.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] There are also other notations where the gauge parameter is the inverse of λ, usually denoted ξ (see *R*ξ gauges).
[src:greens-functions/propagator] The name of the propagator, however, refers to its final form and not necessarily to the value of the gauge parameter.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] Note that upon taking the limit $H\to 0$ and $\Box \to -k^{2}$ , the AdS propagator reduces to the Minkowski propagator.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] The scalar propagators are Green's functions for the Klein–Gordon equation.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] There are related singular functions which are important in quantum field theory.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] These functions are most simply defined in terms of the vacuum expectation value of products of field operators.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] We can define the positive and negative frequency parts of $\Delta (x-y)$ , sometimes called cut propagators, in a relativistically invariant way.
[src:greens-functions/propagator] The retarded, advanced and Feynman propagators defined above are all Green's functions for the Klein–Gordon equation.
[src:greens-functions/resolvent-formalism] In mathematics, the **resolvent formalism** is a technique for applying concepts from complex analysis to the study of the spectrum of operators on Banach spaces and more general spaces.
[src:greens-functions/resolvent-formalism] Formal justification for the manipulations can be found in the framework of holomorphic functional calculus.
[src:greens-functions/resolvent-formalism] The **resolvent** captures the spectral properties of an operator in the analytic structure of the functional.
[src:greens-functions/resolvent-formalism] Among other uses, the resolvent may be used to solve the inhomogeneous Fredholm integral equations; a commonly used approach is a series solution, the Liouville–Neumann series.
[src:greens-functions/resolvent-formalism] The resolvent of A can be used to directly obtain information about the spectral decomposition of A.
[src:greens-functions/resolvent-formalism] For example, suppose λ is an isolated eigenvalue in the spectrum of A.
[src:greens-functions/resolvent-formalism] That is, suppose there exists a simple closed curve $C_{\lambda }$ in the complex plane that separates λ from the rest of the spectrum of A.
[src:greens-functions/resolvent-formalism] defines a projection operator onto the λ eigenspace of A.
[src:greens-functions/resolvent-formalism] The Hille–Yosida theorem relates the resolvent through a Laplace transform to an integral over the one-parameter group of transformations generated by A.
[src:greens-functions/resolvent-formalism] Thus, for example, if A is a skew-Hermitian matrix, then *U*(*t*) = exp(*tA*) is a one-parameter group of unitary operators.
[src:greens-functions/resolvent-formalism] where the integral is taken along the ray $\arg t=-\arg \lambda$ .
[src:greens-functions/resolvent-formalism] The first major use of the resolvent operator as a series in A (cf.
[src:greens-functions/resolvent-formalism] Liouville–Neumann series) was by Ivar Fredholm, in a landmark 1903 paper in *Acta Mathematica* that helped establish modern operator theory.
[src:greens-functions/resolvent-formalism] The name *resolvent* was given by David Hilbert.
[src:greens-functions/resolvent-formalism] The **second resolvent identity** is a generalization of the first resolvent identity, above, useful for comparing the resolvents of two distinct operators.
[src:greens-functions/resolvent-formalism] When studying a closed unbounded operator A: H → H on a Hilbert space H, if there exists $z\in \rho (A)$ such that $R(z;A)$ is a compact operator, we say that A has compact resolvent.
[src:greens-functions/resolvent-formalism] The spectrum $\sigma (A)$ of such A is a discrete subset of $\mathbb {C}$ .
[src:greens-functions/resolvent-formalism] If furthermore A is self-adjoint, then $\sigma (A)\subset \mathbb {R}$ and there exists an orthonormal basis $\{v_{i}\}_{i\in \mathbb {N} }$ of eigenvectors of A with eigenvalues $\{\lambda _{i}\}_{i\in \mathbb {N} }$ respectively.
[src:greens-functions/resolvent-formalism] Also, $\{\lambda _{i}\}$ has no finite accumulation point.
